    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "materializes (Rom. 8:21), it is like tasting of the tree that could have given Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]` eternal life (see Gen. 2:9, 16). The corrupt \u201cSeptuagint\u201d conjectures, \u201cA good desire is a tree of life,\u201d which means nothing practically, doctrinally, theologically, or spiritually. \u201cThe desire\u201d can be applied to \u201cthe desire of all nations\u201d (Hag. 2:7) according to Luke 17:22: that is, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ. Practically, any fulfilled desire gives encouragement and strength to the one who looks forward to it. But we must be careful not to stretch the application, for the flesh is peculiar in that it maintains unquenchable desires which can never be fully satisfied, nor do they nourish the fleshly practitioner (Rom. 7; Gal. 5\u20136). \u201c Whoso despiseth the word shall be destroyed\u201d (vs. 13). This is one of the great\nverse 12, which see. Again, the Vulgate and the Septuagint garble the text till it is unintelligible. The trouble seems to be that the writers (Jerome, Origen, Pamphilus, Clement, Philo, et al.) cannot connect the second clause with the first one. However, this is falling into the age old trap that God set for men like Origen, Augustine, and Calvin. This trap is the deliberate placing together of two dissimilar thoughts after running a series of connected thoughts. The dead orthodox intellectual will become rigid in \u201clogic tight compartments\u201d and assume that the style must continue as it has run. [Note how the entire Graf-Wellhausen school (1800\u20131900) got caught in this same trap when it came to the \u201cstyles\u201d of the authors of the Old Testament.] A careful reader will observe that many times the proverbs are not placed in perfect synthetical or antithetical positions (note Prov. 14:9, 17, 17:19, 19:2, 19:22). \u201c But it is abomination to fools to depart from evil\u201d (vs. 19). A fool hates to \u201cget right\u201d as much as a just man hates to \u201cget wrong\u201d (cf. 29:27). A just man recognizes that a departure from evil is evidence of understanding (Job 28:28); to the fool, \u201cdeparting from evil\u201d is an evidence of a lack of broad mindedness and common sense (Prov. 14:16). To bring the proverb down to earth in the twentieth century: it is an abomination for a fool to quit drinking, dancing, gambling, scheming, and loafing; and to \u201cdepart\u201d from such pleasures as telling dirty jokes, wasting the afternoon watching television, sleeping off a hangover Sunday morning, and betting on horses would be to commit spiritual suicide. The very thought of tithing an income to God, spending Saturday night studying the Bible, and spending Thursday night visiting sick people in the hospitals is enough to turn the fool\u2019s stomach. \u201cIt is abomination\u201d to him. \u201c He that walketh with wise men...but a companion of fools\u201d (vs. 20). This is another one of the great verses in the book of Proverbs, comparable to 13:13, 11:30, 14:12, 18:12, and 21:\nverse 12 [v_Rom_8_21] materializes (Rom. 8:21), it is like tasting of the tree that [v_Gen_2_9] could have given Adam `[char_Adam_Luk_3]` eternal life (see Gen. 2:9, 16). The corrupt \u201cSeptuagint\u201d conjectures, \u201cA good desire is a tree of life,\u201d which means nothing practically, doctrinally, theologically, or spiritually. \u201cThe desire\u201d can be applied [v_Hag_2_7] to \u201cthe desire of all nations\u201d (Hag. 2:7) according to [v_Luk_17_22] Luke 17:22: that is, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ. Practically, any fulfilled desire gives encouragement and strength to the one who looks forward to it. But we must be careful not to stretch the application, for the flesh is peculiar in that it maintains unquenchable desires which can never be fully satisfied, nor do they nourish the fleshly practitioner (Rom. 7; Gal. 5\u20136). \u201cWhoso despiseth the word shall be destroyed\u201d (vs. 13). This is one of the great",
